"I hope Korea will return to GSOMIA." - Yahoo!
U.S. Undersecretary of State for the United States, Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for South Korea and Japan, responded to a single interview by the Sankei Shimbun at the official residence of the U.S. Ambassador in Tokyo on November 27.
It is unusual for a high-ranking U.S. official to refer to a reconsideration of GSOMIA's destruction.
GSOMIA is based on the agreement between Japan, Korea, the United States, and the United States, and the Republic of Korea to share missile launch information.
In August, Korea announced that it would destroy the agreement with Japan, and if it expires, the framework for protecting military information will collapse.
"Without GSOMIA, we cannot effectively respond to the crisis."
"There is time to expire," he strongly urged the return of Korea.
He also pointed out that the joint flight training conducted in July over the Sea of Japan was the first time in history.
He pointed out that the recent deterioration in Japan-Korea relations "damaged the national interests of the United States."
"There is no intention of intermediation," he said, "We will play a positive role to fill the gap."
