Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries (Gifu Shimbun Web) - Yahoo!
On March 27, the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries released a draft amendment to the Anti-Defection Guidelines to prevent the spread of the "Ton cholera" disease, which is not currently recognized.
The province will select nine prefectures, including Gifu Prefecture and Aichi Prefecture, where pigs and wild boars have been identified.
Live pigs and fertilized eggs vaccinated are restricted to the region, but the distribution of meat and processed foods is permitted.
After making public comments to the general public (the public offering of opinions), we aim to complete the procedure as early as October.
By using vaccines and allowing extraterrestrial distribution such as meat, it is no longer a "clean country" certified by international organizations and may affect the export of pork.
Since the outbreak of September last year, Japan has been temporarily suspended.
In the revised plan, the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries set up a "prevention area" based on the opinions of experts regarding areas with high risk of infection from wild boar to pigs.
The target prefecture will create a "vaccination program" that summarizes the scope, time, number of heads, how to proceed, etc.
Seven other prefectures that are recommended for vaccination are Saitama, Toyama, Ishikawa, Fukui, Nagano, Mie and Shiga.
When the guidelines have been revised, the region will review the situation and make a decisive decision.
The movement of inoculated pigs, semen, fertilized eggs, corpses, and excreted objects is limited in principle to the region.
As for meat and processed products, they are not targeted based on the cost of distribution restrictions and the impact on farmers, and they practically accept distribution outside the country.
In order to prevent viruses from spreading, we will thoroughly process food waste.
He also advocates the safety of inoculated pigs and works to prevent harmful rumors.
The amendments to the Guidelines were compiled at an expert meeting held on the same day and confirmed at a meeting of the Anti-Defection Control Headquarters.
In the future, we will conduct opinion inquiries and public comments to prefectures until October 7 and implement new quarantine guidelines.
